<!-- ABOUT -->
<section id="about" class="section-alt">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="about-content" data-scroll-reveal>
      <div class="about-text">
        <h2>About This Book</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Core Concepts in Hindu Philosophy</strong> is an introductory survey that moves systematically through the foundational layers of Hindu thought. The book treats philosophy not as abstract speculation, but as a living tradition where knowledge, ethics, and spiritual discipline converge toward self-realization and liberation.
        </p>
        <p>
          Each section builds on previous concepts, creating a coherent pathway for readers—whether newcomers or scholars deepening their understanding. Clear chapters, comparative tables, a comprehensive glossary, and bibliographies make the material accessible without sacrificing doctrinal accuracy.
        </p>
        <p>
          A standout feature is the chapter on Shuddhadvaita Vedanta, written from within the Pushtimarg tradition with remarkable clarity and warmth—bringing lived philosophical practice into sharp focus.
        </p>
      </div>
